title: Efekt motyla
body:
read it on the AO3 at http://bit.ly/2TOWpoF

by Dramaturgia

Powiadają, że życie składa się z nieustannych decyzji i wyborów, one wszystkie zaś, bez względu na to, jak małe i pozornie nieistotne mogą się zdawać, sprawiają, że znajdujemy się właśnie w tym miejscu, w którym obecnie jesteśmy.
Że każde wypowiedziane słowo, każda iskrząca myśl odbija się echem we wszechświecie, by później ich odzwierciedlenie wróciło do nas w chwili, w której będziemy się tego najmniej spodziewać.
Że wszystko to, co wydarzyło się do tej pory miało swoje miejsce w czasie i przestrzeni tylko po to, byśmy mogli o tym usłyszeć.

Że trzepot skrzydeł motyla jest w stanie wywołać huragan.

title: Beautiful Nightmare 1/18
body:
Pairing: MC!Steve Rogers x Reader

Warning: Language. Violence. Gang issues. Bar brawls. Minor kidnapping. Bleeding. Nightmares.

A/N: I am still writing this. I’m not even sorry. It’s probably junk but I’m in a weird place lately and this is what I decided to write.

You escaped hell. Swore you’d never go back. You live a normal, typical life. Work, friends, home, till one night out changes everything in your life. Meeting Steve was not planned, but now he’s got his eyes set on you.
One date with him sends the two of you into a down spiral. You have to come clean about your past. But what’s hunting you, is it after you or Steve? Can you trust Steve and the Rebel Bastards MC or are you in over your head again?

Tag List Is Open!!
Check the Tag List, if you’re crossed out adjust your settings I’ll remove you after three parts if I still can’t tag you!!

The Throttle was busy, people mingled between the bar, the tables and the dance floor. Music vibrated the walls and kept you from over hearing everyone’s conversations. Mac the bartender is slapping hands with Clint, Steve’s VP. Clint’s working on making his way back to the pool table, Steve’s leaning against. His eyes drift as the music changes and the crowd on the dance floor, straightens out.

He watches the girl he’d seen come in with her two friends. She’s now being dragged out on to the dance floor, laughing. Her cheeks are pink with a buzz, her hair down around her shoulders from the bun she came in with, the sweater she had on was discarded, a little white tank top and jeans as she gives in to her friends.

She falls into step with the others, some line dance bullshit he didn’t know. Her hips swing, her lips singing along, hair bouncing around. He had no shame in his staring at her, she didn’t look like the typical girls that came into The Throttle, it was a biker bar after all. It was actually Rebel Bastard’s bar, they held a stake in the bar, making it their property. Most girls who came in were looking to get noticed, trying to pick up a biker, or trying to get in touch with some small part of them that wanted to be bad.

She runs a hand through her loose hair, laughing as she wiggles around in a circle. Her blonde friends on one side the red head on the other. Hands slap thighs and they turn again, she bounced around in step with those around her. He hadn’t notice Clint had arrived and was standing next to him, lost in his distraction.

“She’s cute.” Clint nods, taking a drink from his beer glass. Steve smirks at him, taking the other glass.

“She doesn’t seem like one to come here.” He takes a drink.

“You know it’s the ones you least expect you have to watch out for.” Clint chuckles, a knowing smirk on his lips. Steve lifts a brow looking over at him.

“Personal experience Barton?”

“Oh yeah.” Clint nods. “She blew my mind, cleaned me out and took my favorite shirt.” Clint flashes a grin at him.

“You seem pretty proud.” Steve shakes his head, laughing.

“Best night of my life to this day.” Clint nods still grinning.

“Oh of course.” Steve snorts, taking another drink of his beer. His eyes finding her on the dance floor, she’s laughing, carefree, even though Steve noticed several men on the edge of the dance floor, around the bar, watching her.

“She doesn’t look like the roll you and bail type.” Clint smirks watching her as well. “But I don’t know if she’s squeaky clean either. My right ear itches looking at her.” He looks over grinning, his hand comes up itching his right ear.

“Trouble?” Steve lifts a brow, smirking. “You get the trouble itch from her? She showed up in a sweater and bun.” Steve points out.

Clint had this itch, his right ear always itched when there was trouble. They used to bullshit with him, asking if he told fortunes as well. Till it saved their asses in a nasty, territory fight, they were being pulled into a trap. Clint’s stupid itch saved half their guys from being gunned down.

“She’s line dancing, hair down, sweater gone, buzz flushed cheeks. I can smell trouble.” Clint laughs.

“Nat just walked by.” Steve smirks, the red head married to Steve’s right hand, Buck walks by flipping him her middle finger.

“That makes sense then.” Clint laughs. Steve watches her as the song comes to an end, she pulls all her hair up off her neck, fanning herself. “She still makes my ear itch.” Clint adds with a smile.

“And the girl who rolled you?” Steve glances over.

“My whole ear was burning.” Clint grins.

“I’m sure.” Steve nods, pushing off the pool table. He sets his beer down and picks up the pool stick.



He leans in to line up his shot.  A tap on his shoulder, makes him glance back. Sam stood shifty behind him. He straightens up, Sam steps closer.

“Keep your eyes on the tender.” He explains, both of them glance at the bar, Mac giving some girl a sleezy grin.

“Why? Dipping or more?” Steve looks back to Sam. Dipping into the till would get Mac beat down, more would get Mac in a body cast and run out of town.

“More.” Sam admits, shaking his head.

“Who?” Steve pulls up to his full height. It was one thing to hit on the girls, it was another to being more than flirty. They couldn’t stand for that in one of their businesses or in association to their club.

“Mrs. heard a few of the girls complaining about him. Sleezy shit.” Sam explains, meaning his wife Wanda was doing her job, she and Nat were to make sure there were no issues for the woman in their establishments.

“Tell Clint to perch at the bar. He sees it. Step in.” Steve orders.

“I’ll pass that down.” Sam nods, turning he heads off to find Clint. Steve turns around looking at Luke who was waiting for him to take his shot.

“It’s so much fun being the Pres, huh?” Luke chuckles.

“Get ready big guy. May need you to throw a lesson out tonight.” Steve smirks, taking his shot.

“With pleasure, boss.” Luke grins.

The two of them look over towards the bar, Clint’s at the end, eyes watching Mac. The girl he’d been watching, she’s heading for the bar with her friends, and something makes him look over at Clint. Clint’s hand comes up itching his right ear as he tracks Mac moving around the bar. Instinct told him to pay close attention, something was coming. He didn’t know her, didn’t know her name, but if Mac touched her, Luke would be doing more than teaching a lesson tonight.

Warning: Language. Violence. Gang issues. Bar brawls. Minor kidnapping. Bleeding. Nightmares.

A/N: I am still writing this. I’m not even sorry. It’s probably junk but I’m in a weird place lately and this is what I decided to write.

You escaped hell. Swore you’d never go back. You live a normal, typical life. Work, friends, home, till one night out changes everything in your life. Meeting Steve was not planned, but now he’s got his eyes set on you.
One date with him sends the two of you into a down spiral. You have to come clean about your past. But what’s hunting you, is it after you or Steve? Can you trust Steve and the Rebel Bastards MC or are you in over your head again?

Tag List Is Open!!
Check the Tag List, if you’re crossed out adjust your settings I’ll remove you after three parts if I still can’t tag you!!

[[MORE]]

The Throttle was busy, people mingled between the bar, the tables and the dance floor. Music vibrated the walls and kept you from over hearing everyone’s conversations. Mac the bartender is slapping hands with Clint, Steve’s VP. Clint’s working on making his way back to the pool table, Steve’s leaning against. His eyes drift as the music changes and the crowd on the dance floor, straightens out.

He watches the girl he’d seen come in with her two friends. She’s now being dragged out on to the dance floor, laughing. Her cheeks are pink with a buzz, her hair down around her shoulders from the bun she came in with, the sweater she had on was discarded, a little white tank top and jeans as she gives in to her friends.

She falls into step with the others, some line dance bullshit he didn’t know. Her hips swing, her lips singing along, hair bouncing around. He had no shame in his staring at her, she didn’t look like the typical girls that came into The Throttle, it was a biker bar after all. It was actually Rebel Bastard’s bar, they held a stake in the bar, making it their property. Most girls who came in were looking to get noticed, trying to pick up a biker, or trying to get in touch with some small part of them that wanted to be bad.

She runs a hand through her loose hair, laughing as she wiggles around in a circle. Her blonde friends on one side the red head on the other. Hands slap thighs and they turn again, she bounced around in step with those around her. He hadn’t notice Clint had arrived and was standing next to him, lost in his distraction.

“She’s cute.” Clint nods, taking a drink from his beer glass. Steve smirks at him, taking the other glass.

“She doesn’t seem like one to come here.” He takes a drink.

“You know it’s the ones you least expect you have to watch out for.” Clint chuckles, a knowing smirk on his lips. Steve lifts a brow looking over at him.

“Personal experience Barton?”

“Oh yeah.” Clint nods. “She blew my mind, cleaned me out and took my favorite shirt.” Clint flashes a grin at him.

“You seem pretty proud.” Steve shakes his head, laughing.

“Best night of my life to this day.” Clint nods still grinning.

“Oh of course.” Steve snorts, taking another drink of his beer. His eyes finding her on the dance floor, she’s laughing, carefree, even though Steve noticed several men on the edge of the dance floor, around the bar, watching her.

“She doesn’t look like the roll you and bail type.” Clint smirks watching her as well. “But I don’t know if she’s squeaky clean either. My right ear itches looking at her.” He looks over grinning, his hand comes up itching his right ear.

“Trouble?” Steve lifts a brow, smirking. “You get the trouble itch from her? She showed up in a sweater and bun.” Steve points out.

Clint had this itch, his right ear always itched when there was trouble. They used to bullshit with him, asking if he told fortunes as well. Till it saved their asses in a nasty, territory fight, they were being pulled into a trap. Clint’s stupid itch saved half their guys from being gunned down.

“She’s line dancing, hair down, sweater gone, buzz flushed cheeks. I can smell trouble.” Clint laughs.

“Nat just walked by.” Steve smirks, the red head married to Steve’s right hand, Buck walks by flipping him her middle finger.

“That makes sense then.” Clint laughs. Steve watches her as the song comes to an end, she pulls all her hair up off her neck, fanning herself. “She still makes my ear itch.” Clint adds with a smile.

“And the girl who rolled you?” Steve glances over.

“My whole ear was burning.” Clint grins.

“I’m sure.” Steve nods, pushing off the pool table. He sets his beer down and picks up the pool stick.



He leans in to line up his shot.  A tap on his shoulder, makes him glance back. Sam stood shifty behind him. He straightens up, Sam steps closer.

“Keep your eyes on the tender.” He explains, both of them glance at the bar, Mac giving some girl a sleezy grin.

“Why? Dipping or more?” Steve looks back to Sam. Dipping into the till would get Mac beat down, more would get Mac in a body cast and run out of town.

“More.” Sam admits, shaking his head.

“Who?” Steve pulls up to his full height. It was one thing to hit on the girls, it was another to being more than flirty. They couldn’t stand for that in one of their businesses or in association to their club.

“Mrs. heard a few of the girls complaining about him. Sleezy shit.” Sam explains, meaning his wife Wanda was doing her job, she and Nat were to make sure there were no issues for the woman in their establishments.

“Tell Clint to perch at the bar. He sees it. Step in.” Steve orders.

“I’ll pass that down.” Sam nods, turning he heads off to find Clint. Steve turns around looking at Luke who was waiting for him to take his shot.

“It’s so much fun being the Pres, huh?” Luke chuckles.

“Get ready big guy. May need you to throw a lesson out tonight.” Steve smirks, taking his shot.

“With pleasure, boss.” Luke grins.

The two of them look over towards the bar, Clint’s at the end, eyes watching Mac. The girl he’d been watching, she’s heading for the bar with her friends, and something makes him look over at Clint. Clint’s hand comes up itching his right ear as he tracks Mac moving around the bar. Instinct told him to pay close attention, something was coming. He didn’t know her, didn’t know her name, but if Mac touched her, Luke would be doing more than teaching a lesson tonight.

title: Jeremy Whitley on Twitter
excerpt: “Got some DMs this morning from a person concerned about where I stand on trans issues because of something they'd read in another person's tweets. My name was censored so obviously they don't want to talk to me about it and that's cool, but I've been pretty clear about my stance:”
description:
Jeremy Whitley speaks about his opinion on trans rights:

Trans rights are human rights and I stand with the trans community. I also believe trans representation in media is important and so I try to provide that in books where possible, be it in content or, say, in whom I choose to profile or plug.

He also says in the same thread that while he does have trans characters in his creator-owned books, there are characters in his superhero comics he considers trans, but to actually say it on page would require an agreement of “half a dozen people over his head” and he wants to bring it up only if he is sure to have enough room to properly and respectfully handle it. As he admits, even bringing up and apologizing for past slip-ups, this is a topic he still could do better.

- Admin

title: Standing On The Broken Pieces
body:
